---
import SiteLayout from '../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';
---

<SiteLayout
  title="OpenPrinter Alternatives by Ownership Tradeoff"
  description="Practical OpenPrinter alternatives for buyers who want no mandatory ink subscription, lower lock-in risk, refillable ink, or Linux-friendly printing today."
>
  <div class="article">
    <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--amber);">OpenPrinter alternatives</p>
    <h1>Waiting for OpenPrinter? Buy around the lock-in problem today.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      The best alternative is not a single perfect printer. It depends on whether you care most about ink cost, Linux support, text printing, or avoiding subscriptions.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--amber);">Shortlist</p>
          <h2>Choose by the tradeoff you actually need</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
          OpenPrinter's goals cannot be reduced to “cheap ink.” These four documented products solve narrower problems today, while keeping their proprietary boundaries visible.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="decision-grid">
        <article><h3>Refillable color + automatic duplex</h3><p><strong>Epson ET-2850</strong> is the documented match. Verify the model has no “U” suffix.</p></article>
        <article><h3>Refillable color + dual-band Wi-Fi</h3><p><strong>Canon G3270</strong> documents 2.4/5 GHz Wi-Fi and Wireless Direct, but not automatic duplex.</p></article>
        <article><h3>Color office functions</h3><p><strong>Brother MFC-J4335DW</strong> adds ADF, fax, and duplex, using LC406 cartridges rather than bottles.</p></article>
        <article><h3>Linux + local text printing</h3><p><strong>Brother HL-L2460DW</strong> lists Linux, Ethernet, IPP/IPPS, and LPR/LPD; it is monochrome and print-only.</p></article>
      </div>
      <p class="evidence-note">These routes are based on manufacturer documents verified July 22, 2026. The products were not independently tested. See the <a href="/guides/no-subscription-printers/">full field-level reviews</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="article">
    <section class="article-section">
      <h2>How to choose an alternative</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Refillable color:</strong> compare the Epson ET-2850 and Canon G3270, then decide whether automatic duplex matters more than dual-band Wi-Fi.</li>
        <li><strong>Color office functions:</strong> the Brother MFC-J4335DW adds fax and an automatic document feeder but uses proprietary LC406 cartridges rather than bottles.</li>
        <li><strong>Linux and text:</strong> the Brother HL-L2460DW has the clearest official Linux and local-protocol evidence, but it is monochrome and print-only.</li>
        <li><strong>Open hardware:</strong> none of these products is a substitute for an open design. They are conventional proprietary printers with different local-control and supply options.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="article-section">
      <h2>What this comparison cannot promise</h2>
      <p>
        We did not independently test these printers. An optional subscription does not prove account-free setup, and local USB does not prove every maintenance function works without an app. Firmware, supported operating systems, consumable availability, and vendor policies can change. Use the detailed <a href="/guides/no-subscription-printers/">source register and buying checklist</a> immediately before purchase.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</SiteLayout>
